    {%- if page.handle == 'deity-crown-mukut-kireedam-size-guide' -%}
      <h2>Crown measurement checklist before buying</h2>
      <p>Use this checklist when comparing a deity crown, mukut, kireedam or kirita. Idol height gives visual scale, but head or face width, crown height, depth, circumference or arc decide whether the crown is likely to sit properly.</p>

      <h3>Open-back or half crown</h3>
      <p>Measure the idol head or face width where the crown will sit. Compare this with the product width, then check height and depth so the crown does not cover the face, namam, hairstyle, trunk, hands or backdrop.</p>

      <h3>Full-round crown</h3>
      <p>Measure the full circumference around the idol head. Front width alone is not enough for a full-round crown because the crown must pass around the head comfortably.</p>

      <h3>Curved crown or hair crown</h3>
      <p>Measure the visible front arc and the depth needed for hair, bun, saree drape or goddess-style back placement. Check side photos when the idol head is tilted or has raised hair detail.</p>

      <h2>Deity-specific fit notes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lakshmi, Varalakshmi and Amman:</strong> check face width, hairstyle, saree drape and whether the crown should sit upright, tilted or with a hair-crown look.</li>
        <li><strong>Balaji, Vishnu and Perumal:</strong> check crown height with namam or thiruman, shanku chakra, shoulder ornaments and long haram placement.</li>
        <li><strong>Krishna and Radha Krishna:</strong> check peacock feather, flute position, head angle and whether the style is Krishna-specific or a general crown by size.</li>
        <li><strong>Ganesha and Ganapati:</strong> check trunk direction, ear width and head shape. A crown that fits a narrow idol may not fit a broad Ganesha head.</li>
      </ul>

